A row has ensued between the lawmaker representing lseyin/ltesiwaju/ Kajola/lwajowa Federal Constituency at the House of Representatives, Hon. Shina Peller and the Nigerian Security and Civil Defence Corps (NSCDC) after the lawmaker sponsored a bill seeking to scrap the agency. Peller, in the synopsis on the bill, described the NSCDC as a waste of money and duplication of the functions of the police Hours after the lawmaker sponsored the bill, a viral letter signed by Sotiyo Igbalawole on behalf of the Oyo NSCDC commandant, ordered the withdrawal of NSCDC officers attached to Peller.   Jibrin: Wike restated southern governors’ position on zoning     One feared dead, other injured in Kwara hijab crisis     Ladoja joins kingmakers to endorse Balogun as next Olubadan   But the Oyo Command where the letter purportedly emanated from denied and described the letter as fake. - Advertisement - The Commandant-general of the Nigeria Security and Civil Defence Corps (NSCDC), Ahmad Audi, ordered reinstatement of the officers. Spokesman for the agency, Odumosu Olusola said the letter from the Oyo Commandant was sent “without clearance,” adding that the officer who ordered the withdrawal acted out of line. The Nation learnt that the bill, which has passed first reading, seeks to establish a transition management committee to superintend the agency, develop regulations and implement procedures for the transfer of assets and personnel of the corps to the Nigeria Police Force (NPF). The NSCDC Act of 2003 led to the establishment of the agency under former President Olusegun Obasanjo.